# CIBMTR - Equity in Post-HCT Survival Predictions

# Overview

In this competition, I will develop models to improve the prediction of transplant survival rates for patients undergoing allogeneic Hematopoietic Cell Transplantation (HCT). This is an important step in ensuring that every patient has a fair chance at a successful outcome, regardless of their background.

## Description

Improving survival predictions for allogeneic HCT patients is a vital healthcare challenge. Current predictive models often fall short in addressing disparities related to socioeconomic status, race, and geography. Addressing these gaps is crucial for enhancing patient care, optimizing resource utilization, and rebuilding trust in the healthcare system.

This competition encourages participants to advance predictive modeling by ensuring that survival predictions are both precise and fair for patients across diverse groups. By using synthetic data—which mirrors real-world situations while protecting patient privacy—participants can build and improve models that more effectively consider diverse backgrounds and conditions.

## Evaluation Criteria

The evaluation of prediction accuracy will involve a specialized metric known as the **Stratified Concordance Index (C-index)**, adapted to consider different racial groups independently. This method allows us to gauge the predictive performance of models in a way that emphasizes equitability across diverse patient populations.

### Concordance Index

- **0.5**: Expected result from random predictions
- **1.0**: Perfect concordance
- **0.0**: Perfect anti-concordance

### Stratified Concordance Index

For this competition, the standard C-index is adjusted to account for racial stratification, ensuring that each racial group's outcomes are weighed equally in the model evaluation. The stratified C-index is calculated as the mean minus the standard deviation of the C-index scores calculated within the recipient race categories.

